<TEXT>
airlines must respond to government alerts of 
terrorist threats but could face fines if they disclose them to the 
public under a federal aviation administration order to take effect 
monday 
the order replaces the system of issuing security bulletins that 
brought criticism from relatives of victims of the bombing of pan am 
flight 103 over scotland in december that killed 270 people 
the new system however rejects the relatives demand that 
passengers on any flight be advised of threats against their flight 
instead airlines that disclose such threats without faa 
authorization would face a 10000 fine individuals could be fined 
1000 
transportation secretary samuel skinner who announced the faa 
order friday earlier said such disclosures would compromise 
security and disrupt commercial aviation 
faa spokesman john leyden said the new system for alerting 
airlines will include two types of advisories information circulars 
and security directives 
the information circulars will deal with general threats of 
hijackings bombings or other terrorist actions leyden said 
they are basically a headsup warning and would require no 
particular action he said 
the stronger security directives however would require 
countermeasures by an airline such as additional baggage 
inspections leyden said these would be in response to specific 
threats against an airline an airport or an individual flight and 
might include such information as the threatened time and method of 
attack he said 
until now airlines have not been required to take any specific 
actions in response to security bulletins although steps were 
sometimes recommended 
before the bombing of flight 103 notices of threats against us 
airlines on the flights route were posted in at least one foreign 
embassy but not distributed to the general public the state 
department later said the bulletin should not have been posted in 
its moscow embassy and that no information about threats is supposed 
to go to government employees that does not also go to the public 
us and european authorities later said they concluded the 
threat was a coincidence and not related to the bombing of flight 
103 
other warnings were issued before the flight about the 
possibility of plastic explosives concealed in a radiocassette 
player investigators concluded that such a bomb caused the pan am 
explosion although they have not determined who planted the device 
the faa in a news release on the new order said airlines have 
been responsive to actions suggested in security bulletins but 
making compliance mandatory will strengthen security 
since 1986 the faa has issued 93 security bulletins about 
onethird of them warning of specific threats 
on thursday the faa announced new rules requiring airlines to 
install devices that can detect plastic explosives in checked 
luggage at 40 us and foreign airports 
it did not list the airports except for john f kennedy in new 
york and gatwick in london and said it would take up to three years 
for all the screening devices to be installed 
</TEXT>
