<DOCNO> AP890708-0149 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the question of whether big is better is 
dominating the accounting industry where the big eight flock of 
firms threatens to dwindle to the even bigger big five 
the mergers recently announced or currently being contemplated by 
these huge firms are confounding some experts who question not only 
whether the combinations are necessary but how clients ultimately 
will fare 
i just dont understand what theyre after said abraham 
briloff professor emeritus of accounting at bernard m baruch 
college in manhattan how big does bigness have to be 
the answer is pretty big chicagobased arthur andersen amp co and 
new yorks price waterhouse confirmed this past week they had 
entered into formal talks about merging their worldwide operations 
if completed the combination would be the worlds largest accounting 
firm with annual worldwide revenue of 5 billion and domestic 
revenue of 27 billion 
together the two firms would audit almost 40 percent of the 
companies in the fortune 500 
experts in the hotly competitive field said they believed 
andersen and price waterhouse raced their announcement to the public 
to steal some thunder from deloitte haskins amp sells and touche ross 
amp co 
deloitte and touche ross which share the bottom rungs of the big 
eight ladder said they planned to join forces creating the 
thirdlargest accounting firm 
the merger wave within the admittedly staid industry began weeks 
ago when ernst amp whinney and arthur young amp co said they were 
teaming up in a merger that will create the worlds biggest firm 
but the glory of being no 1 may be fleeting as ernst amp young would 
be eclipsed by an andersenwaterhouse combination 
the firms say they are being driven by the increasing 
globalization of world economies accelerating technological changes 
and demand for new services and investments 
arthur bowman atlantabased publisher of bowmans accounting 
report said 1992 the year europe will meld into one economic 
market is spurring firms to position themselves to better win and 
serve foreign clients 
in addition the firms are seeking to blanket the united states 
with a cadre of highly qualified personnel a commodity sometimes 
difficult to come by 
but briloff argued that the firms can serve clients effectively 
without merging within each organization they have enough 
personnel scattered around the globe to take care of the largest 
multinational corporations and if they dont they can just go out 
and hire 
large corporations wont suffer from the mergers but 
middlemarket companies those with sales under 100 million or so 
could find themselves shunted aside experts say 
in recent years highly specialized consulting services have 
become a greater source of revenue for the big eight in 1984 for 
example the firms collectively drew 9355 million in revenue from 
consulting services last year that figure jumped to 21 billion 
according to bowman 
while each big eight firm serves small businesses experts say 
service to those companies sometimes is uneven 
are the major firms going to want to be price competitive for 
emerging companies or will they wait till these companies need a 
basket of services that they can more efficiently produce said 
gary previts professor of accountancy at case western reserve 
university in cleveland 
not all businesses need a large organization many corporations 
prefer firms that are still small enough to provide personal 
service said stuart kessler senior tax partner at goldstein 
golub kessler amp co in manhattan 
the cpa traditionally has been the consultant that does the 
handholding and i dont know how you do handholding when youve got 
thousands of offices he said 
indeed bowman contends that local accounting firms might find it 
easier to win small business clients because the the big firms 
are going to get so large they cant handle them 
while the consolidations are likely to result in the layoff of 
support staff and some professionals fees charged to clients are 
expected to remain unaffected 
there wont be any efficiencies in the audit and tax returns by 
becoming larger kessler said 
concern also swirls in the academic community where professors 
fear their students will have fewer job offers from which to choose 
but kessler says that could be a boon for secondtier accounting 
firms which also are on the lookout for new talent 
