<TEXT>
when time inc and paramount communications inc 
bring their takeover battle before chancellor william t allen on 
tuesday they will face a jurist who is highly regarded by legal 
scholars including some who disagree with him 
hes really an extraordinary judge said james d cox a 
professor at duke university law school he brings the acuity of 
years of practice as well as a very outstanding academic bent 
which is something characteristic of the very best judges in 
american jurisprudence 
however cox said i find myself wincing more often than not 
with the results hes reached 
melvin a eisenberg a professor at the university of california 
at berkeley law school said of allen i disagree with a lot of 
his results but hes a very intelligent judge who has a very 
lively active mind 
such praise takes on even greater significance when considered in 
light of the role allens court plays in shaping us corporate law 
because nearly half of the fortune 500 companies are incorporated in 
delaware a decision in one case can have broad ramifications for 
other companies 
allen who heads delawares chancery court in wilmington on 
tuesday is to hear arguments on what could be the pivotal issue in 
the struggle for time paramount which has bid 122 billion for 
time contends the time board put the company up for sale in march 
when it agreed to a friendly merger with warner communications inc 
under the laws of delaware where all three companies are 
incorporated if a company has put itself on the block its board 
must consider whatever bids will give stockholders the maximum value 
for their shares if allen agrees with paramount it would be 
difficult for the time board to reject the 200 a share offer 
observers say it is hard to predict how allen might rule 
i dont think you can pigeonhole him said eisenberg 
michael bradley a university of michigan law professor said 
allen takes a middle of the ground conservative approach to 
takeovers 
bernard black a professor at the columbia university school of 
law called allen moderately proshareholder in the sense that 
hes shown some willingness at the end of the day to say 
ultimately the shareholders have the right to decide what they want 
to do 
however black said i would emphasize the words moderately 
and some 
allens past rulings give few clues as to how he might decide 
this case 
in march allen said the board of tw services inc which was 
fighting a hostile bid from the investor group coniston partners 
was not required to submit the unwanted offer to stockholders 
the judge acknowledged that corporate democracy is a pertinent 
concept but he added directors not shareholders have 
responsibilities to manage the business and affairs of the 
corporation subject however to a fiduciary obligation 
allen made the statement in a decision upholding tws poison 
pill takeover defense but in another case last year he struck 
down interco incs poison pill saying the companys board had 
tried to use the defense to prevent shareholders from deciding 
between the companys recapitalization plan and a hostile bid from 
investors steven and mitchell rales 
allen declined requests for an interview but he has acknowledged 
the significance of the timeparamount hearing 
late last month he refused to hold hearings on paramounts 
request to block times annual meeting the judge said it was more 
important to spend his time preparing for tuesdays session 
cox the duke professor said allen is aware of delawares 
influential role in us corporate law 
delaware court decisions have determined the outcome of many big 
takeover battles in recent years including grand metropolitan plcs 
successful pursuit of pillsbury co last year and shamrock holdings 
incs failed hostile bid for polaroid corp earlier this year 
but these decisions affect more than just the parties involved in 
a particular takeover fight they serve as precedents that can 
affect future confrontations and companies contemplating their 
strategies are mindful of past decisions 
allens decision in time which undoubtedly will be appealed by 
the losing side could affect friendly mergers planned by other 
companies 
allen 44 a graduate of new york university and the university 
of texas law school in austin practiced for 11 years with a 
wilmington firm before joining the chancery court 
he is an active participant in hearings questioning attorneys as 
they make their arguments and exhibiting a dry sense of humor like 
other judges on the chancery court he sometimes adds an air of 
informality to his courtroom presiding in a business suit rather 
than a judges trademark black robe 
allen joined the chancery court in 1985 the court which has 
five judges has a crowded calendar and at times has had to recruit 
retired judges to help with the caseload 
late last year retired judge william duffy was called back to 
the bench to preside over suits involving one of 1988s megadeals 
grand metropolitans buyout of pillsbury duffys ruling 
invalidating pillsburys poison pill was seen as a key factor in 
getting the company eventually to end months of resistance and agree 
to a 568 billion buyout 
